{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CreT4N3EhFPiQRBonQLNsq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Prometheus ConfigMap only has a self-scrape job. I need to add RabbitMQ scrape jobs. \n\nThe RabbitMQ metrics are on port 15692/metrics. I need to scrape all 3 pods individually. \n\nLooking at the services:\n- `rabbitmq` ClusterIP service on port 15692 - this would only scrape one target\n- `rabbitmq-headless` - None (headless) - this can be used for pod-level discovery\n\nThe best approach for scraping all 3 pods individually is to use the headless service with DNS-based discovery or use Kubernetes service discovery. Let me think about the options:\n1. **Static config with headless service DNS** - The headless service creates DNS records for each pod: `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.NAMESPACE.svc.cluster.local`, `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.NAMESPACE.svc.cluster.local`, `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.NAMESPACE.svc.cluster.local`. This is simple and doesn't require CRDs.\n\n2. **Kubernetes SD (service discovery)** - Use `kubernetes_sd_configs` with `role: pod` and label selectors. This is more dynamic.\n\nI should check what Prometheus version is running to understand which features are available.\n\nFor simplicity and reliability, I'll go with static configs using the headless service DNS names. Each StatefulSet pod gets a predictable DNS entry, so I can target all three RabbitMQ instances individually on port 15692 without needing any CRDs. Now I need to look at how Prometheus itself is deployed to see how to integrate this configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":430,"cache_read_input_tokens":31666,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":430},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_man